WEBVTT

00:00.000 --> 00:07.000
You know, usually when we talk about a medical diagnosis, there's this expectation of precision.

00:07.520 --> 00:10.360
Right. It feels almost like engineering in a way.

00:10.560 --> 00:15.980
Exactly. I mean, you break your arm, the x-ray shows that jagged white line in the bone,

00:16.020 --> 00:20.300
and the doctor just points at it and says, yep, there it is. That is the problem.

00:20.400 --> 00:24.000
It's totally binary. The fracture is either there or it isn't.

00:24.080 --> 00:24.300
Yeah.

00:24.300 --> 00:28.140
And I think that visibility is incredibly comforting.

00:28.140 --> 00:35.200
Like, we have this deep psychological need for our problems to be categorized and visible.

00:35.740 --> 00:39.400
Yeah. But then you step into the world of complex systems, right?

00:39.500 --> 00:46.700
Like neurodevelopment or chronic autoimmune conditions, and suddenly that x-ray machine is just useless.

00:47.080 --> 00:48.400
Oh, completely useless.

00:48.840 --> 00:48.980
Yeah.

00:49.000 --> 00:53.400
You are looking at a diagnostic landscape that is entirely murky.

00:53.400 --> 00:58.880
Right. You know something is fundamentally wrong. You feel the pain of it every single day.

00:59.020 --> 01:03.360
But the machine can't capture it because the problem isn't a single broken bone.

01:04.180 --> 01:08.360
I mean, the problem is the invisible relationship between a million different moving parts.

01:08.360 --> 01:17.960
And that transition, you know, from looking for a single point of failure to trying to understand a systemic condition,

01:17.960 --> 01:21.260
it requires a completely different set of tools.

01:21.420 --> 01:25.740
You basically have to stop looking at static images and start looking at dynamics.

01:25.740 --> 01:31.040
I bring up that broken x-ray machine because today, for you, the learner tuning in,

01:31.160 --> 01:34.700
we are going into a system that is fundamentally broken.

01:35.220 --> 01:39.960
But the diagnosis has been intentionally obscured for a century.

01:40.600 --> 01:41.760
Yes, it really has.

01:41.880 --> 01:43.360
Welcome to the Deep Dive.

01:43.740 --> 01:53.800
We are taking on an incredibly dense, genuinely mind-bending academic paper from 2026 by an independent researcher named Flyxion.

01:53.800 --> 01:55.480
Which is quite the read.

01:55.620 --> 02:04.920
Yeah, to put it mildly, it's titled Escape Velocity, Austerity, Field Dynamics, and the Endogenous Regulation of Transformation.

02:05.320 --> 02:14.120
And at its core, this text is arguing that our economic and social systems have an invisible architecture designed specifically to keep us trapped.

02:14.300 --> 02:16.440
And it uses high-level physics to prove it.

02:16.520 --> 02:17.680
Right. It's wild.

02:17.820 --> 02:18.940
So what's our mission today?

02:18.940 --> 02:26.720
We are going to unpack this so you can walk away with these mind-bending insights without having to decipher the differential equations yourself.

02:27.320 --> 02:30.660
Which is a relief because it is a formidable piece of literature.

02:31.380 --> 02:33.840
The mathematical equations alone are daunting.

02:34.640 --> 02:37.700
But the underlying concept is just a revelation.

02:38.120 --> 02:38.920
It really is.

02:39.120 --> 02:45.560
The premise revolves around taking a concept straight out of astrophysics, which is escape velocity.

02:45.560 --> 02:56.740
Right, which, you know, in literal rocket science is the minimum kinetic energy an object needs to break free from a massive body's gravitational pull.

02:57.260 --> 02:57.800
Exactly.

02:58.060 --> 03:03.860
If your rocket doesn't hit that exact velocity, the math is unforgiving.

03:04.660 --> 03:06.540
You are pulled back down to the surface.

03:06.860 --> 03:13.520
And Flyxion is taking this immutable law of physics and overlaying it onto political economy.

03:13.520 --> 03:21.320
They are essentially saying that our society, our economic paradigm, generates its own gravitational field.

03:21.540 --> 03:22.660
Which is a heavy thought.

03:22.980 --> 03:28.560
But before we get too deep into the gravity of it all, we should probably set some boundaries for this discussion.

03:28.940 --> 03:30.800
Yeah, that is a trusel point.

03:31.180 --> 03:39.580
What makes Flyxion's paper so unique, and frankly so powerful, is that it strips away the political ideology we usually attach to these conversations.

03:39.580 --> 03:43.760
Because it relies on some pretty politically charged history, right?

03:44.140 --> 03:44.740
It does.

03:45.600 --> 03:50.800
The text relies heavily on the historical analysis of an economist named Clara Maté.

03:51.440 --> 03:57.400
It looks at the history of capitalism, austerity, and even the rise of fascism in the 1920s.

03:57.800 --> 04:06.080
But, and this is important for you listening, the paper ignores the standard left-wing versus right-wing ideological debates.

04:06.080 --> 04:09.980
Right. It doesn't ask you to agree with Maté's politics.

04:10.640 --> 04:13.820
We are not taking political sides here. At all.

04:14.200 --> 04:21.420
We aren't endorsing any left-wing or right-wing views, or advocating for the emancipatory strategies mentioned in the text.

04:21.560 --> 04:26.940
Exactly. We are strictly here to explore the structural and mathematical arguments.

04:26.940 --> 04:38.820
Yes. The goal is purely analytical. It treats historical governments and modern tech monophilies as mechanical systems operating on the exact same underlying geometry of constraint.

04:39.200 --> 04:44.780
Which is incredibly liberating for us, honestly, because we don't have to wade into a partisan debate today.

04:44.900 --> 04:45.360
Not at all.

04:45.580 --> 04:47.680
We are just looking at the architecture.

04:47.960 --> 04:48.100
And?

04:48.100 --> 04:50.380
We are looking at the math of social gravity.

04:50.380 --> 04:58.240
And to understand how this gravity is manipulated, Flyxion argues we have to throw out our traditional view of the economy.

04:58.420 --> 05:00.160
Yeah. The way we usually look at it.

05:00.420 --> 05:04.300
Right. Because we are so used to seeing the economy as a ledger.

05:04.720 --> 05:10.020
We look at GDP. We look at inflation rates. We look at who owns how many resources.

05:10.380 --> 05:12.420
It's basically an accounting spreadsheet.

05:12.420 --> 05:20.280
And the author argues that the spreadsheet model is entirely inadequate for understanding systemic change.

05:21.000 --> 05:22.400
So what do they replace it with?

05:22.580 --> 05:29.860
Instead, Flyxion models the economy as a coupled state-field representation.

05:30.300 --> 05:36.780
Okay. A coupled state-field representation. That is a really heavy phrase. Let's translate that for a second.

05:36.940 --> 05:37.120
Sure.

05:37.120 --> 05:45.000
In physics, a field is a region where each point has a particular physical quantity associated with it.

05:45.400 --> 05:48.900
Like, um, a magnetic field around a magnet.

05:49.220 --> 05:50.100
Yes. Exactly.

05:50.280 --> 05:58.580
The text is suggesting the economy operates the same way, defined by a system they call X, which is made up of three interacting variables.

05:58.920 --> 06:00.960
And those are phi, V, and S.

06:01.280 --> 06:05.000
Right. So the formula is X equals phi, V, S.

06:05.000 --> 06:11.120
Let's pull those three variables apart, because they really form the epistemic scaffold for the entire paper.

06:11.320 --> 06:16.260
These aren't just metaphors. I mean, Flyxion treats them as a geometric organization of reality.

06:16.420 --> 06:17.960
Okay. Let's start with the first one.

06:18.340 --> 06:24.320
The first variable is phi. This represents structural constraint and the distribution of resources.

06:25.160 --> 06:30.200
The text describes it as the depth of the potential well that a society sits in.

06:30.200 --> 06:40.000
So if phi is the potential, well, in real-world terms, we're talking about the physical and economic barriers to survival, right?

06:40.020 --> 06:40.460
Exactly.

06:40.460 --> 06:55.940
Like, wealth inequality would deepen phi, or a system where you absolutely must sell your labor every single day just to afford food and shelter that makes the walls of the well incredibly steep, you have zero buffer.

06:55.940 --> 07:03.320
That is an excellent way to frame it. Phi is the asymmetrical distribution of power mapped out as a physical landscape.

07:03.800 --> 07:06.440
So a shallow well is easy to get out of.

07:06.540 --> 07:15.400
Yes. If phi is shallow, movement is easy. You can quit your job, take a risk, maybe try a new way of living without the fear of immediate starvation.

07:15.540 --> 07:15.900
Right.

07:15.900 --> 07:26.900
But if phi is beep, the gradient of the well is so steep that it takes immense continuous kinetic energy just to maintain your current position, let alone climb out.

07:26.980 --> 07:30.740
You're just constantly climbing just to not fall. Okay, so what's the second variable?

07:31.200 --> 07:39.380
The second variable interacting with this landscape is V. This is directed agency, or the vector field of coordinated movement.

07:39.720 --> 07:45.160
I found V fascinating because it's not just a measure of, like, are people active?

07:45.160 --> 07:46.560
No, not at all.

07:46.740 --> 07:49.460
Because a crowded city street is active, right?

07:49.760 --> 07:50.020
Yeah.

07:50.120 --> 07:58.280
But everyone is walking in different directions. That's just thermal noise. The text really emphasizes coordinated movement.

07:58.440 --> 08:10.640
That's the key. The author uses empirical proxies to measure VR. Things like the density of union membership or sustained participation in neighborhood assemblies.

08:10.780 --> 08:11.860
It's about alignment.

08:11.860 --> 08:19.820
Yes. It is the measure of how well individual trajectories can be aligned into a coherent collective thrust.

08:20.000 --> 08:20.440
Got it.

08:20.620 --> 08:26.300
If V is highly aligned, it's like a strong magnetic field pointing in one unified direction.

08:26.480 --> 08:27.280
And if it's not?

08:27.600 --> 08:33.840
If V is fragmented, you have millions of people struggling violently, but their vectors cancel each other out.

08:34.100 --> 08:38.220
They push in opposite directions, resulting in zero systemic movement.

08:38.220 --> 08:48.540
Okay. And then we have the third variable, S. This stands for configurational accessibility. And I'll be honest, this one felt the most abstract to me.

08:48.900 --> 08:50.860
It can be a bit tricky to grasp at first.

08:51.420 --> 08:59.040
The text defines it as the logarithmic volume of alternative trajectories that are dynamically reachable.

08:59.040 --> 09:04.280
Yeah. So, it helps to think of S as the phase space of admissible futures.

09:04.840 --> 09:06.360
Meaning what? Exactly.

09:06.600 --> 09:18.140
It is not about what you can simply imagine in your head. It is about what institutional, legal, or policy pathways are actually open to you in reality.

09:18.540 --> 09:18.980
Ah.

09:18.980 --> 09:30.440
So, if you want to build a completely new type of cooperative, decentralized energy grid, you have to ask, does the legal framework even allow for that?

09:30.580 --> 09:30.840
Right.

09:30.980 --> 09:39.720
Do the financial institutions offer capital for it? If they don't, that future is foreclosed. It is structurally inaccessible.

09:39.720 --> 09:44.560
So, S basically measures the sheer volume of those accessible alternatives.

09:44.740 --> 09:45.140
Exactly.

09:45.360 --> 09:51.800
Okay. Let's unpack this for the learner. I want to use an analogy here. Imagine you're in a massive multiplayer video game.

09:52.120 --> 09:53.400
Okay. I like where this is going.

09:53.640 --> 09:56.960
V is the gravity and the map's physical barriers.

09:57.280 --> 09:57.400
Yeah.

09:57.400 --> 10:02.000
Like, how steep the hills are, how hard it is to just survive in the environment.

10:02.620 --> 10:07.460
And V is how well the players are coordinating their movements together, like a guild.

10:07.460 --> 10:11.060
Are they working as a team or just running around randomly?

10:11.420 --> 10:13.120
Yes. The alignment of agency.

10:13.540 --> 10:20.580
And S is the underlying code that dictates what futures or endings are even programmed into the game.

10:20.920 --> 10:27.900
Like, if the developers didn't code a specific ending, you literally cannot reach it, no matter how hard you try.

10:28.240 --> 10:29.840
That is a perfect analogy.

10:30.100 --> 10:30.320
Yeah.

10:30.320 --> 10:46.740
And if we view the economy through this game engine lens, we can look back at history and see exactly when those in power manipulated the gravity, the player coordination, and the game code to prevent people from escaping the current level.

10:46.840 --> 10:49.100
Which means we can't just change one thing.

10:49.980 --> 10:55.520
Escaping a basin of attraction requires a coordinated transformation across all three fields.

10:55.520 --> 10:59.040
The mutual dependence is the genius of the model.

10:59.580 --> 11:03.180
You cannot achieve escape velocity by altering just one variable.

11:03.640 --> 11:13.220
If you have a deep well, hi-fi, and a disorganized population, a fragmented V, it doesn't matter if you have a great idea for a new society, which is S.

11:13.300 --> 11:15.760
Exactly. You don't have the kinetic energy to get there.

11:15.760 --> 11:27.840
And, conversely, if people are organized, high V, and ready to climb out, but the system has shut down all alternative pathways, low S, they just hit a brick wall.

11:28.100 --> 11:37.400
Right. And while it is tempting to view this through a localized individual lens, Flyxion applies this at the macroeconomic level.

11:37.600 --> 11:41.440
Which brings us to one of the most volatile periods in modern history.

11:41.440 --> 11:49.300
The text leans heavily on Maddy's historical reconstruction of the 1920s, right after the First World War.

11:49.980 --> 11:50.860
Why start there?

11:51.360 --> 11:59.720
Because, according to this framework, that was a moment when the escape velocity of global capitalism almost plummeted to zero.

11:59.720 --> 12:04.720
The post-WWI era is really a perfect laboratory for this theory.

12:05.380 --> 12:12.940
Because the war had completely shattered the illusion that the pre-1914 economic order was the only way to run a society.

12:13.140 --> 12:14.260
I mean, everything changed.

12:14.340 --> 12:19.720
During the conflict, the state had taken over mass production, prices were controlled, and millions of men were conscripted.

12:20.580 --> 12:22.700
The unimaginable had become reality.

12:22.760 --> 12:24.380
Which radically expanded us.

12:24.620 --> 12:28.200
Exactly. The space of admissible futures expanded.

12:28.200 --> 12:38.020
People realized that if the government could organize the entire economy to fight a war, it could organize the economy to benefit the working class in peacetime.

12:38.360 --> 12:41.680
And the vector field, V, was highly aligned, too.

12:41.900 --> 12:51.020
You had returning soldiers who were organized, you had a massive surge in union membership, and of course you had the looming shadow of the 1917 Russian Revolution.

12:51.300 --> 12:54.440
Showing that workers actually could overthrow a state.

12:54.440 --> 13:04.060
Right. So, V is aligned, S is expanded, and the potential well of fee had been temporarily flattened by wartime employment and inflation.

13:04.440 --> 13:06.900
The math was terrifying for the establishment.

13:07.740 --> 13:09.860
The workers were reaching escape velocity.

13:10.120 --> 13:16.220
And this is where the paper argues that our conventional historical understanding is just fundamentally flawed.

13:16.460 --> 13:18.900
Yes, it challenges the standard narrative.

13:18.900 --> 13:27.220
When we look at the policies enacted by the British establishment in the 1920s policies, we broadly label as austerity.

13:27.640 --> 13:33.180
We tend to view them as necessary, albeit painful fiscal housekeeping.

13:33.660 --> 13:39.840
We think of austerity as a government trying to balance its checkbook after a costly war.

13:40.180 --> 13:43.960
Right. But Flyxion argues this is a profound misreading.

13:43.960 --> 13:48.080
Completely. Austerity wasn't about balancing a budget.

13:48.520 --> 13:56.040
It was a highly sophisticated, deliberate strategy to raise the escape velocity back to an insurmountable level.

13:56.480 --> 14:08.240
I want to really dig into the mechanics of this, because the way the text describes Britain's return to the gold standard is chilling when you view it through this fueled theory.

14:08.480 --> 14:09.960
It is a striking example.

14:09.960 --> 14:18.300
So in 1925, Winston Churchill, as Chancellor of the Exchequer, returns Britain to the gold standard at the pre-war parity.

14:18.700 --> 14:22.740
In textbook economics, that's just a monetary policy choice.

14:23.300 --> 14:28.820
But in Flyxion's framework, how did this actively deepen the potential well of feel?

14:29.360 --> 14:34.740
To understand the mechanism, we have to look at what returning to the pre-war parity actually did in practice.

14:34.980 --> 14:35.300
Okay.

14:35.300 --> 14:39.000
During the war, Britain had printed money, causing inflation.

14:39.140 --> 14:39.340
Right.

14:39.400 --> 14:44.200
Returning to the old exchange rate essentially made the British account artificially expensive.

14:44.360 --> 14:45.560
Which hurts exports.

14:46.000 --> 14:51.900
Right. This immediately made British exports, like coal, uncompetitive on the global market.

14:52.380 --> 14:56.340
To compete, the mine owners had to drastically slash prices.

14:56.760 --> 14:59.240
And the only way to do that was to slash wages.

14:59.240 --> 15:03.440
Wow. So the gold standard wasn't just a currency peg.

15:03.720 --> 15:11.660
It was an external, seemingly objective mechanism used to force wage reductions across the entire working class.

15:11.760 --> 15:12.260
Precisely.

15:12.900 --> 15:19.880
It systematically decoupled survival from mere labor and tied it to a brutally steep gradient of effort.

15:20.580 --> 15:24.900
By depressing wages, the establishment radically deepened phi.

15:24.900 --> 15:30.100
So the working class had to expend all their available energy just to avoid starvation.

15:30.780 --> 15:33.520
They were thrust to the very bottom of the potential well.

15:34.220 --> 15:39.680
But the establishment knew that a deep well isn't enough if the workers are still coordinated.

15:40.120 --> 15:42.320
They had to break the vector field deep.

15:42.600 --> 15:47.060
And the paper details how they did this by utilizing unemployment as a weapon.

15:47.920 --> 15:51.260
They didn't view joblessness as a tragedy to be solved.

15:51.420 --> 15:54.120
They viewed it as a disciplinary tool.

15:54.120 --> 15:54.640
Exactly.

15:55.640 --> 16:01.660
When you restrict credit and raise interest rates to protect the gold standard, you intentionally contract the economy.

16:02.180 --> 16:05.420
Businesses close and millions of people are thrown out of work.

16:05.540 --> 16:07.660
Which creates a reserve army of labor.

16:08.180 --> 16:08.580
Yes.

16:09.340 --> 16:11.660
Now, think about what this does to V.

16:11.660 --> 16:29.420
If you are a coal miner considering a strike, your alignment with your fellow workers is instantly fragmented by the terrifying realization that there are 10 starving men outside the gate willing to take your job for half the pay.

16:29.680 --> 16:31.240
The coordination just shatters.

16:31.520 --> 16:34.220
The magnetic field loses its polarity.

16:34.220 --> 16:39.000
Everyone is forced into a localized individual struggle for survival.

16:39.880 --> 16:42.400
You turn against your neighbor out of pure desperation.

16:42.920 --> 16:45.100
So fee is deepened by wage cuts.

16:45.480 --> 16:48.300
V is fragmented by weaponized unemployment.

16:48.740 --> 16:50.260
And what happens to S?

16:50.260 --> 16:52.560
Well, S is implicitly compressed.

16:53.440 --> 17:05.580
Because the government has tied its own hands with the gold standard, any alternative future, like a massive public works program or state investment in housing, is rendered mathematically impossible under the rules of the system.

17:05.640 --> 17:06.420
Oh, that's clever.

17:06.420 --> 17:07.080
Very.

17:07.640 --> 17:11.060
The government can simply throw up its hands and say, well, we'd love to help.

17:11.460 --> 17:13.620
But the rules of the gold standard forbid it.

17:14.040 --> 17:15.880
It's just the invisible hand of the market.

17:16.240 --> 17:18.380
The space of admissible futures collapses.

17:18.740 --> 17:20.540
It's an incredible sleight of hand.

17:20.780 --> 17:24.920
The violence of the policy is hidden behind the sterile language of central banking.

17:25.460 --> 17:26.160
It really is.

17:26.160 --> 17:36.680
But if that was the British approach, the text contrasts this with a much darker, much more overt response happening simultaneously in Italy.

17:37.020 --> 17:37.520
Indeed.

17:38.320 --> 17:45.740
While Britain managed the threshold through liberal austerity, Italy managed it through fascist austerity.

17:45.740 --> 17:51.860
And this is where Flyxion's reliance on Maddy's work becomes conceptually brilliant, right?

17:52.060 --> 17:52.540
Absolutely.

17:52.540 --> 18:02.500
Italy, in the early 1920s, the Bienio Rosso, or the two red years, saw an even more dramatic lowering of the escape velocity.

18:02.840 --> 18:06.260
Workers were physically occupying factories in Turin.

18:06.680 --> 18:08.320
They were forming worker councils.

18:08.800 --> 18:15.180
The coordination of V was at an unprecedented high, and the potential well of V was rapidly shallowing.

18:15.900 --> 18:20.740
The liberal state was practically collapsing under the kinetic energy of the working class.

18:20.740 --> 18:24.500
And the system's immune response to that was Benito Mussolini.

18:24.640 --> 18:24.920
Yes.

18:25.160 --> 18:28.740
But Flyxion points out that Mussolini wasn't just a political dictator.

18:28.980 --> 18:31.040
He was an economic threshold manager.

18:31.980 --> 18:36.200
How did fascist corporatism manipulate Phi, V, and S?

18:36.340 --> 18:40.280
Because they certainly didn't rely on the polite fiction of the invisible hand.

18:40.520 --> 18:41.980
No, they definitely didn't.

18:42.480 --> 18:48.120
The structural outcome was identical to Britain, but the modalities were entirely distinct.

18:48.120 --> 18:51.540
Let's look at V, the coordinated agency.

18:52.400 --> 18:57.760
Mussolini didn't just passively rely on unemployment to break union solidarity.

18:58.080 --> 18:58.760
What did he do?

18:59.080 --> 19:07.940
Through the Vidoni Pact of 1925 and subsequent labor laws, the fascist regime violently outlawed independent trade unions.

19:08.300 --> 19:12.080
Wait, they literally made independent coordination illegal?

19:12.080 --> 19:14.940
Yes, and they didn't just leave a vacuum.

19:15.120 --> 19:19.520
They forced all capital and labor into state-controlled syndicates.

19:20.240 --> 19:22.140
This is a crucial distinction in the math.

19:22.220 --> 19:22.780
How so?

19:22.900 --> 19:25.880
They didn't just shatter the vector field into thermal noise.

19:26.340 --> 19:33.200
They coercively captured the vectors and forced them into a state-mandated alignment that served the regime.

19:33.700 --> 19:37.100
The autonomous capacity of V was completely neutralized.

19:37.100 --> 19:37.540
Wow.

19:38.260 --> 19:48.840
And for fee, they instituted direct wage controls and abolished the right to strike, locking the workers into a deepened well through police violence rather than central bank policy.

19:48.980 --> 19:49.500
Yes, I see.

19:49.640 --> 19:51.860
And S obviously is compressed to zero.

19:52.180 --> 19:57.060
I mean, in a totalitarian state, the only admissible future is the one dictated by the leader.

19:57.060 --> 20:02.680
The paper uses this comparison not to shock, but to prove a mathematical point.

20:03.820 --> 20:11.580
Flyxion emphasizes that there is a structural continuity between liberal austerity and fascist economic policy.

20:11.780 --> 20:14.480
Right, but we need to be really clear here for the listener.

20:15.040 --> 20:23.540
Are we really saying liberal British economic policy and authoritarian Italian fascism were doing the exact same thing?

20:23.640 --> 20:26.260
That is a very uncomfortable comparison.

20:26.260 --> 20:29.220
It is, but the text is very careful here.

20:29.620 --> 20:32.520
This is not a claim of moral or political equivalence.

20:32.580 --> 20:33.120
Okay, good.

20:33.300 --> 20:42.920
A liberal democracy that uses interest rates to discipline labor is not the same thing as a fascist dictatorship that uses black shirts to murder union leaders.

20:43.040 --> 20:43.300
Right.

20:43.700 --> 20:50.520
The text makes it very clear liberalism distributes the constraints so that it feels like impersonal natural laws.

20:50.520 --> 20:56.400
Fascism concentrates the constraint into a central, visible, coercive authority.

20:56.480 --> 20:56.960
Exactly.

20:57.680 --> 21:02.880
But the result on the equation X equals 5VS is exactly the same.

21:03.520 --> 21:09.360
The escape velocity is raised to an impossible height and the prevailing basin of attraction is preserved.

21:09.840 --> 21:10.980
The system survives.

21:10.980 --> 21:17.460
And understanding that structural continuity is essential for the next major argument in the text.

21:17.940 --> 21:29.220
Because if these massive macroeconomic manipulations of the field are constantly occurring, how does it actually feel for the individuals living inside that map?

21:29.220 --> 21:34.720
That brings us to what Flyxion calls the phenomenology of trajectory tension.

21:35.140 --> 21:41.020
This was the part of the paper that honestly forced me to put it down and just stare at the wall for a minute.

21:41.180 --> 21:42.700
It hits very close to home.

21:42.700 --> 21:59.820
It does, because we've been talking about 5V and S as abstract variables managed by chancellors and dictators, but the text pivots beautifully here to explain how this global field structure translates into our daily lived reality.

22:00.380 --> 22:04.120
